A 25 kilogram mass hemisphere of Heu  that is surrounded by 1 inch thick hollow  hemisphere berylium tamper   will not be critical because it leaks to many neutrons out of it due to its geometric shape.<br>
But when I fire a second 25 kg Heu hemisphere into it<br>
that is also surrounded by a 1 inch thick hollow berylium hemisphere tamper, the two hemispheres will form a common ball of supercritical mass, and produce an atomic explosion.<br>
This is because the neutron free path for untamped material<br>
must be at least 10.72 centimeters  to achieve  a 67% probability that each neutron will cause a fission event in the uranium ball.The berylium tamper by reflecting neutrons back into the sphere when they leak out of it can double the statistical proability that each nuetron will cause a fission event in the ball. This results in supercriticaility when the uranium 235 hemispheres are assembled into a comman ball<br>
by the gun.10.72 cm is 4.22 inches. This results in an 8.44 <br>
inch diameter pit that has a 4.22 inch radius. As a result the U-235 ball becomes very supercritical after its assembly.<br>
A 67 % probability is not required to achieve supercriticality.<br>
<br>
 2.5-3/2 neutrons  = 1.25-  1.5 neutrons  with a neutron free path of 5.36 cm is enough to achieve a barely crital configuration (critical mass )  If the tamper however reflects the neutrons back into the ball when they leak out of it  this increases the probability of fission by up to a factor of two thus rendering it supercritical,.<br>
Note that the probabity of fission needs to be increased by <br>
the tampers reflection of neutrons by just 20% to render the atomic core supercritical .*<br>
Tim<br>
