 will make a barely critical configuration  when <br>
the U-235 ball is fully assembled.<br>
It does not become supercritical until  it is surrounded by the 1 inch thick berylium tamper/neutron reflector.Without the berylium reflector it is just barely critical after assembly<br>
Before assembly the probability of a fission event being <br>
caused by a free neutron is just  50 %  without the tamper . This represents a sub critical configuration before core assembly occurrs. With out the tamper a 5.36 cm radius ball is sub critical. With out the tamper an  8 cm radius ball<br>
is just barely crital after assembly occurrs. <br>
A U 235 ball with a 5.36 cm radius measures just 4.24 inches in diameter. The assembled ball of U 235 is about 8.5 inches in diameter + the 1 inch berylium  tamper.<br>
A free nuetron can travel only 16 cm through an air gap with out a 100% probability of absorption by the atoms in the air.<br>
16 cm is 6.3 inches . The air gap between the pieces of the pit thus keeps them supercritical. A barely critical core configuration is not achieved until the pieces of the core are less then 6.3 inches distant from each other. <br>
Thus the air gap in the gun also keeps the U-235 <br>
 pieces subcritical before core assembly occurrs.<br>
Tim<br>
