in a material of its normal density does not control the length of its free path. How many collisions the free neutron will have with other atoms determines the probability of its absorption by an atom when it collides with it..<br>
U- 235 atoms are much more massive then those of the air but there are many more of them,and thus there are many more  colllisions for the neutron then there is in the uranium.<br>
To be absorbed by an atom a neutron must be slowed down to the right energy,and the velocity range by its collisions with other atoms while traveling on its mean free path.<br>
A neutron must be slowed down enough by colliding with other atoms before it can  absorbed by a fissile atom and thus cause a fission. It it is absorbed by a non-fissile atom the neutron  can change an atom of of one non fissile element<br>
into an atom of a different element, or it cause cause an atom of an element to change into a different isotope of the same element when it is absorbed.<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1>Open Forum</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.31b<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  